	title={`Bible Verses for Veterans — Free with Audio | Father's Heart Bible™`}
	description={`Bible verses and encouragement for veterans, free with audio. You carry what most will never see — but you were never forgotten, and never meant to carry it alone.`}
	h1={`The Bible for Veterans`}
	heroEyebrow={`A Father For`}
	heroSubhead={`You served. You sacrificed. You carry what most people will never see. And underneath the homecoming, the transition, the things you don't talk about — there is a Father who never left your side, who calls you His own beyond the uniform.`}
	heroBase={`https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/754e1eadc7743bff7e1d0df927a35bff2806ae31-1100x734.jpg`}
	heroAlt={`A veteran in an American Legion cap standing among flags at a memorial`}
	heroObjectPosition={`center center`}
	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you've worn the uniform, the Father's Heart Bible™ is for you.</strong> You came home carrying things most people will never understand — the weight of what you saw, the friends who didn't make it back, the strange quiet of civilian life, the question of who you are now. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free on your phone — and it reveals God as a <em>Father</em> from beginning to end. Whether you searched "Bible verses for veterans," "scripture for soldiers," "encouragement for veterans," or "verses for PTSD" — the answer starts in one place: you were never forgotten, and you were never meant to carry it alone. You have a Father who never leaves, and a name beyond the uniform.`}
	keyTakeaway={`Your worth was never the mission, the rank, or the uniform you wore. You were never forgotten by your Father — He stood with you in every hour, and He gives you a name and a home that no discharge can take away.`}
	painsHeading={`The weight veterans carry home`}
	painsIntroHtml={`If you feel unseen, restless, or like part of you is still over there, you are not broken and you are not alone. A whole community of veterans carries the same weight — and the numbers say it out loud.`}
	painStats={[
		{ value: `About 7%`, label: `of veterans will experience PTSD at some point in their lives — higher than the general population (VA, National Center for PTSD)` },
		{ value: `44%`, label: `of post-9/11 veterans say their readjustment to civilian life was difficult (Pew Research)` },
		{ value: `47%`, label: `of post-9/11 veterans report frequently feeling disconnected from civilian friends and family after service (Pew Research)` },
		{ value: `About 1 in 4`, label: `post-9/11 veterans say they had trouble paying bills in the first few years after leaving the military (Pew Research)` },
		{ value: `17.6`, label: `veterans died by suicide each day in 2021 — every one a life that mattered and a loss that was not inevitable (VA, 2023 National Veteran Suicide Prevention Annual Report)` },
		{ value: `Over half`, label: `of service members and veterans who report mental-health struggles say stigma or self-reliance kept them from seeking help (RAND)` },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every statistic is a real person — maybe you. The nights sleep won't come. The crowd that puts you on edge. The empty chair at the table for the ones who didn't come home. The civilian world that says "thank you for your service" and then has no idea what to say next. The quiet grief of a mission, a unit, and a purpose that used to define your days.</p><p>None of this means something is wrong with you. It means you carried something heavy and real, and you carried it for people who will never know your name. There is a Father who saw every hour of it — every deployment, every loss, every silent struggle since you came home — and He has something to say about who you are now.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `VA — 2023 National Veteran Suicide Prevention Annual Report`, url: `https://www.mentalhealth.va.gov/docs/data-sheets/2023/2023-National-Veteran-Suicide-Prevention-Annual-Report-FINAL-508.pdf` },
		{ label: `Pew Research — The American Veteran Experience and the Post-9/11 Generation`, url: `https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2019/09/10/the-american-veteran-experience-and-the-post-9-11-generation/` },
		{ label: `RAND — Invisible Wounds of War: Psychological and Cognitive Injuries`, url: `https://www.rand.org/pubs/monographs/MG720.html` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for veterans`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here's what the homecoming parades and the bumper stickers never tell you: the answer to what you carry isn't being forgotten and it isn't gritting your teeth and carrying it alone. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — a perfect, faithful Father who never left your side, not for one hour of one deployment, and who loves you today, exactly as you are.</p><p>You were trained to be self-reliant, to hold the line, to never leave a fallen comrade behind. But you were never meant to carry the invisible wounds alone. The One who made you doesn't measure you by the mission, your rank, or whether you feel strong today. He calls you His own — not the soldier you were, not the version that has it all together, but <em>you</em>, right now, in this season of coming home.</p><p>So before you're a veteran, a survivor, a name on a service record — you are His. Your heavenly Father wants to be the steady presence underneath the noise, the one who says: I was with you the whole time, I never forgot you, and you have a home and a name with Me that no discharge can ever take.</p>`}
