	keepReadingHtml={`Start with the <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">whole Bible free online with audio</a>, learn <a href="/the-fathers-heart-bible/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">why the Father's Heart Bible™ exists</a>, or get oriented with our <a href="/guides/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Bible reading guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how to pray</a> and <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>. Or meet the Father in another season through the rest of the <a href="/bible-for/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">A Father For series</a>.`}
	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for veterans?`, answer: `Deuteronomy 31:6 (He will never leave you nor forsake you), Psalm 34:18 (close to the brokenhearted), Isaiah 41:10 (I will strengthen you and uphold you), Psalm 147:3 (He heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds), Joshua 1:9 (be strong; your Father is with you wherever you go), Psalm 23:4 (through the darkest valley, He is with you), Isaiah 43:1 (I have called you by name, you are Mine), and John 14:27 (My peace I give to you) all speak straight to what veterans carry. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about PTSD and the wounds veterans carry?`, answer: `Scripture takes invisible wounds seriously and offers a real place to bring them. Psalm 147:3 says God heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds, and Psalm 34:18 promises He is close to the brokenhearted and saves the crushed in spirit. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father you can actually hand the weight to — read those passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What scripture helps with survivor's guilt or the loss of friends in service?`, answer: `Psalm 34:18 and Psalm 147:3 speak directly to grief and a crushed spirit — God draws near to the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds. Psalm 23:4 walks with you through the darkest valley, and John 14:27 offers a peace the world cannot give. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who saw every loss and grieves with you — read and listen free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does God still see me after I've left the military?`, answer: `Yes — and He never stopped. Deuteronomy 31:6 says He will never leave you nor forsake you, and Isaiah 43:1 says He has called you by name and you are His. Your worth was never your rank or your role. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who was with you through every deployment and welcomes you home with a name beyond the uniform. Read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about fear, anxiety, and finding peace?`, answer: `Philippians 4:6-7 says don't be anxious about anything, but bring your requests to God, and His peace will guard your heart and mind. Isaiah 41:10 says do not fear, for He is with you and will uphold you, and John 14:27 gives a peace the world can't give. Read these free, with audio, in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio for veterans?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read on your phone and read or hear any book — perfect for a long drive, a sleepless night, or the quiet before a hard appointment.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for veterans?`, answer: `It's the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of a distant commander handing down orders, you meet the One who stood with you the whole time and welcomes you home. For someone carrying what most will never see, that reframes everything: you come to the Bible as a loved and welcomed child first, not a soldier reporting for inspection.` },
	]}
